    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-16T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-16T22:00:00-05:00" n="743"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d743">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.20/327: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-17T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >April 17, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 17—4:58 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>With reference to last paragraph of your telegram 121, March 29, 5 p.m., I learn
                    that the Chinese Government for various reasons does not consider it expedient
                    to take the matter up through its Legation in Washington and that <persName
                        corresp="#p_STV1">Soong</persName> is therefore continuing his conversations
                    with Trade Commissioner <persName corresp="#p_HEP1">Howard</persName> here
                    regarding civilian aviation. Has the Department any objection?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
